    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1938-06-27T00:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1938-06-27T00:00:00-05:00" n="503"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d503">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.003/898: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1938-06-27T14:00:00+09:00"
                            >June 27, 1938—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received June 27—7:18 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>416. Department’s 211, June 25, 2 p.m.—extraterritorial status of Americans.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Representations as desired by the Department were made to the Foreign
                        Office today.<note n="85" xml:id="d503fn85">See memorandum of June 27, <ref
                                target="frus1931-41v01#pg_769">
                                <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931–1941, vol. <hi
                                    rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 769</ref>.</note> We referred to the
                        Shanghai case described in the Department’s 384, December 30, 1 [<hi
                            rend="italic">3</hi>] p.m.<note n="86" xml:id="d503fn86">
                            <ref target="frus1937v04#pg_426">
                                <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1937, vol. <hi
                                    rend="smallcaps">iv</hi>, p. 426</ref>.</note> and to the
                        interview which I had with Hirota<note n="87" xml:id="d503fn87">Koki Hirota,
                            Japanese Minister for Foreign Affairs until May 26.</note> on January 10
                        recalling that I had stated that the American Government would not recognize
                        or give countenance to any attempt on the part of the Japanese to assert
                        jurisdiction over American citizens. The Foreign Office replied that a
                        telegram had been received over the week-end from the Japanese Ambassador at
                        Washington who reported that the statement of the Japanese Embassy’s
                        spokesman at Shanghai had been prominently carried in the American press and
                        had shocked the American public. The Foreign Office has taken steps to
                        obtain from Shanghai the text <pb facs="0382" n="378" xml:id="pg_378"/> of
                        the statement under reference. We intend therefore to make a further
                        approach in the matter either tomorrow or the day after.<note n="88"
                            xml:id="d503fn88">See memorandum of June 30, <ref
                                target="frus1931-41v01#pg_770">
                                <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, Japan, 1931–1941, vol. <hi
                                    rend="smallcaps">i</hi>, p. 770</ref>; also see memorandum of
                            July 4, <ref target="frus1931-41v01#pg_605">
                                <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, pp. 605</ref>, <ref
                                target="frus1931-41v01#pg_609">609</ref>–<ref
                                target="frus1931-41v01#pg_610">610</ref>.</note>
                    </item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>In the absence of any official information on the subject, the Foreign
                        Office was reluctant to express any opinion. We pointed out however that if
                        the Japanese Government were to confirm and approve the statement made as
                        reported, the position of the Japanese Government would be open to most
                        serious implications including that of claiming rights of sovereignty in the
                        areas under Japanese occupation in disregard of treaty commitments and
                        declarations with regard to respecting the territorial integrity of
                        China.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>My British colleague informs me that he is making representations on this
                        matter this afternoon.</item>
                </list>
                <p>Repeated to Shanghai for Hankow.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
